All Superinterfaces:

public interface ListSortedInterface<T extends lsdn.KeyedItem<S>,S extends java.lang.Comparable<S>>
extends java.lang.Iterable<T>, lsdn.Execute<T>

This interface describes the behavior that any type of sorted list should have. Items in the list must extend KeyedItem so that they can be located by search key. Search keys should be immutable but they must be at least Comparable to compare search keys. T is the KeyedItem class, and T must be using S as its search key. A given search key must be unique in the list.

add

void add(T item)
         throws lsdn.ListException
Add an item to the list in ascending order by search key.
Preconditions:
item is the KeyedItem to be inserted into the list
item is not null and has a search key that is not already present in the list
Postconditions:
the item is inserted into the list in ascending order by search key (if the preconditions are met)
otherwise, item is unaffected
Throws: ListException if item is null or there is an item with search key sk already in the list

Throws:
lsdn.ListException

get

T get(S sk)
Returns the KeyedItem with search key sk.
Preconditions:
search key (sk) is not null
Postconditions:
the item with search key sk is returned if such an item is present
null is returned if no items in the list have search key sk
sk itself is unaffected
Throws: none

remove

void remove(S sk)
            throws lsdn.ListException
Removes the item with the provided search key from the list.
Preconditions:
search key (sk) is not null
a KeyedItem with the provided search key (sk) is present in the list
Postconditions:
the item with the provided search key is removed from the list
the remaining items are in ascending order by search key
otherwise, sk is unaffected
Throws: ListException if sk is null or an item with search key sk is not present in the list

Throws:
lsdn.ListException
